//TC-O(n log n)
//SC-O(n)
class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) { //O(n)
            return false;
        }
        char[] s1 = s.toCharArray(); //O(n)
        char[] s2 = t.toCharArray(); //O(n)
        Arrays.sort(s1); //O(n log n)
        Arrays.sort(s2); //O(n log n)
        return Arrays.equals(s1, s2); //O(n)
    }
}

//TC-O(n)
//SC-O(k)  k = number of distinct characters
class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) {
            return false;
        }
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(c, map.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);
        }
        for (char c : t.toCharArray()) {
            Integer count = map.get(c);
            if (count == null) {
                return false;
            }
            if (count == 1) {
                map.remove(c);
            } else {
                map.put(c, count - 1);
            }
        }
        return map.isEmpty();
    }
}

//TC-O(n)
//SC-O(1)
class Solution {
    public boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
        if (s.length() != t.length()) {
            return false;
        }
        int[] freq = new int[26];
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            freq[c - 'a']++;
        }
        for (char c : t.toCharArray()) {
            freq[c - 'a']--;
            if (freq[c - 'a'] < 0)
                return false;
        }
        return true;
    }
}
Summary
Solution	Time	Space
Sorting	O(n log n)	O(n)
HashMap	O(n)	O(k), worst case O(n)
Frequency Array	O(n)	O(1)

Only the HashMap solution needs a small correction.

Which Solution Should You Discuss?

This is where interview strategy matters.

Option 1: Start with Sorting

If you immediately see the optimal solution, don't spend 10 minutes explaining sorting.

A brief mention is enough:

"A straightforward solution is to sort both strings and compare them. That takes O(n log n) time and O(n) extra space because of the character arrays. I think we can do better using frequency counting."

This shows that you considered a simpler baseline before optimizing.

Option 2: Move to HashMap

Next, explain:

"We can count the frequency of every character in the first string and decrement the counts while scanning the second string. If a character is missing or its count goes below zero, the strings are not anagrams."

This demonstrates the key idea behind the optimal algorithm for arbitrary character sets.

Then mention:

"This runs in O(n) time with O(k) extra space, where k is the number of distinct characters."

Option 3: Optimize Further

Finally, if the interviewer says:

"The strings contain only lowercase English letters."

Now say:

"Since the character set is fixed, we don't need a HashMap. We can replace it with an int[26] frequency array."

This is the optimal solution under the given constraints.

What I'd Expect from a 5-Year Java Developer

If I asked Valid Anagram in an interview, the ideal flow would be:

1. Clarify assumptions

"Are the strings guaranteed to contain only lowercase English letters?"

If the interviewer says:

Yes

Go directly to the frequency array solution.

If they say:

No

Go directly to the HashMap solution.

Then add:

"If the character set were restricted to lowercase English letters, I'd replace the HashMap with an int[26] to reduce the space from O(k) to O(1)."

This shows adaptability and awareness of constraints.

My Recommendation for You

For your interview preparation notebook, document all three solutions in this order:

Sorting — Easy baseline, O(n log n), O(n).
HashMap — General-purpose solution, O(n), O(k) (worst case O(n)), works for arbitrary characters.
Frequency Array — Best solution when the alphabet is fixed, O(n), O(1).

That progression demonstrates both problem-solving evolution and the ability to choose the right data structure based on the problem constraints—exactly what interviewers want to see.
